      <text xml:space="preserve" bytes="1393">{{Translated page|pl|Bomba mezonowa}}
{{milhist|class=start|Weaponry=y}}
{{DYK talk|29 February|2016|entry= ... that during the [[Cold War]], American intelligence tricked [[Soviet atomic bomb project|Soviet nuclear researchers]] into working on a nonsensical '''[[meson bomb]]'''?|nompage=Template:Did you know nominations/Meson bomb}}
Could we do a little more than just translate this? The article mentions a U.S. disinformation effort as having been successful, but does little to describe how the idea was used to mislead the Soviets. Which is to say, it does ''nothing''. [[User:Daniel Case|Daniel Case]] ([[User talk:Daniel Case|talk]]) 17:41, 29 February 2016 (UTC)
:'''Addendum''': After reviewing the cited source, I think this &quot;disinformation&quot; claim should be taken with a grain of salt. It comes from a Soviet nuclear weapons researcher who recalls that he, and others with his level of qualification, doubted the idea of the bomb strongly, but then saw their superiors invest considerable time and money in researching it anyway. Therefore, he concludes the whole idea was American disinformation.&lt;p&gt;I rather think that it demonstrates that [[Hanlon's razor]]—never attribute to malice that which is adequately explained by stupidity—applied on both sides of the [[Iron Curtain]]. [[User:Daniel Case|Daniel Case]] ([[User talk:Daniel Case|talk]]) 19:02, 29 February 2016 (UTC)</text>
